node.text:
Just like consumer cars have to undergo crash testing, so do commercial semitrucks. While some of these tests are the same that production cars undergo, others are designed specifically for trucks. 

Thanks to trucking companies like Volvo and Scania as well as the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety, safety standards for these trucks are only improving.

node.text: Vietnamese woodworker Truong Van Dao built a fully drivable wooden Bugatti. It’s one third the size of an actual car, but a near replica of the luxury automaker’s $8.9 million Centodieci hypercar. We explore how he did the entire project in just 40 days.

node.title: How to build a fully drivable wooden Bugatti

node.text: A wave of upcoming hypercars claim to accelerate 0 to 60 mph in as little as 1.7 seconds. However, nothing has been verified. The reality is that no production car has ever managed an official 0 to 60 time of under 2 seconds. There's a reason for that. We break down how current technology has created that limit, and what could be done to break it.

node.title: Why going 0 to 60 mph in under 2 seconds is almost impossible

node.text:
In 2019, the Bugatti Chiron Super Sport 300  became the first production car to drive 300 mph. This was almost 15 years after the Bugatti Veyron became the first to reach 250. So why did it take so long for automakers to build a car just 50 mph faster? We explore what makes 300 mph such a difficult benchmark to reach and what automakers like Bugatti have been doing to chase it.

#cars #speed #bugatti #sportscar

node.title: Why It's Almost Impossible For Cars To Go 300 Miles Per Hour

node.text:
Has extra government support during the pandemic stopped people from going back to work, or are other factors at play? 

Uber and Lyft executives just waded into this debate, saying the end of unemployment insurance in some US states has spurred more drivers to sign up to their ride-hailing platforms. 

Mostly Republican politicians have argued that the payments have been an incentive for people to avoid returning to work. But experts say other factors are to blame, such as a lack of child care and fear of COVID-19 infection.

Click the link in our bio for more.

(Credit: Getty Images)

node.text:
Apple plans to roll out software on US iPhones that will detect child sexual abuse images, the Financial Times reported. It will then pass the material on to human reviewers who will alert law enforcement if they think the images are illegal.

Security experts warned that this could open the floodgates to extensive surveillance and risks potential backlash from privacy activists.

Click the link in our bio to read the full story.

(Credit: Getty Images)

May be an image of text that says 'INSIDER よ TikTok TikTok is debuting a Stories feature where content will disappear after 24 hours This is another example of the tech industry S most popular platforms swiping ideas from each other.'.

node.text:
TikTok confirmed a new Instagram-like feature to Insider after a Twitter user posted screenshots of it online. 

They said TikTok is "experimenting with ways to give creators additional formats to bring their creative ideas to life for the TikTok community."

It's yet another example of the tech industry's most popular platforms swiping ideas from each other. Instagram launched Stories in 2016 and quickly drew comparisons to Snapchat. And in 2020, the Facebook-owned company debuted a TikTok copycat, Instagram Reels.

Click the link in our bio for more details.

(Credit: Getty Images)

node.accessibility_caption: A photo of online content creator Zach King making a peace sign.

node.text:
Watching a Zach King video is a bit like taking a dip into another dimension, one where paintings are portals to far-reaching locales, video game car chases loop into real-life ones, and mirrors make perfect hiding places.

As TikTok's fifth-most-followed account with nearly 63 million followers, his videos regularly reach millions of viewers — but in some explosively viral instances, he's even reached into the billions, and is the creator of what appears to be TikTok's most-viewed video.

Here's how the filmmaker went from selling film editing tips under the moniker FinalCutKing to being one of the biggest online creators.

(Credit: Rob Latour/Invision/AP)

Facebook's first-ever movie premiere will debut as a ticketed event on Facebook Live, company executives told Axios. The premiere will feature "The Outsider," a controversial documentary that explores the creation of the National 9/11 Memorial and Museum in New York City. 

Officials of the 9/11 Memorial and Museum have called parts of the film "defamatory." Click the link in bio to learn more about Facebook’s first-ever movie premiere. 

Story by Hannah Towey.

(Credit: AP/Getty Images/AP/Reuters)

The movie will be live-streamed exclusively on Facebook for $3.99 on August 19, available to users in over 100 countries.

A graphic that shows an image for Facebook co-founder Mark Zuckerberg. It reads: In June, Facebook CEO Mark Zuckerberg said that content creator features such as live events will remain free until 2023, adding "when we do introduce a revenue share, it will be less than the 30% that Apple and others take."

A graphic that shows first-responders at the 9/11 memorial in New York City. It reads: Museum officials have called some parts of the documentary "defamatory," while directors Steven Rosenbaum and Pamela Yoder said that the museum "censors and controls" reporting about the memorial.

node.text:
A huge Tesla battery pack was on fire for four days until firefighters managed to put it out, Australian local authorities said on Monday.

The "Megapack," at an upcoming Australian power project, caught fire in a trial, authorities said.

Firefighters "found a 13-tonne lithium battery inside a shipping container was fully involved," the CFA said. The exact cause of the fire is still unknown but will be investigated, the CFA said.

The battery plant, first announced in 2019, was built by French renewable energy giant Neoen using Tesla's 300 megawatt battery packs.

node.text:
Doordash workers are using social media platforms such as TikTok and Reddit to strike against their low base pay rates. 

Recent videos claim that DoorDash recently lowered its base pay from $3 to $2.  The majority of "Dashers" will not deliver for DoorDash on July 31st in protest against the pay. 

A spokeswoman for DoorDash confirmed that the company changed their base pay rates to help "Dashers" earn more for completing longer distance deliveries. "Dashers" hope to send a message with the strike.

node.text:
Google Maps has a mapping layer that allows users to see regions color-coded by per-capita number of COVID-19 cases.

The layer color codes areas by the 7-day average for the number of new cases per 100,000 people, and shows if cases are trending up or down.

The feature aims to help users "make more informed decisions about where to go and what to do."

node.text:
According to a recent survey of 1,000 industry workers, a vast majority of tech employees believe technology products are not diverse enough, and neither are the teams that design them. 

Data suggests that ethnic and gender diversity make companies more likely to succeed, but leadership often fails to acknowledge the problem.

Read more about this story by clicking the link in our bio.

Text graphic with the text, "A 2018 McKinsey report found companies in the top 25% for gender diversity on executive teams outperformed more homogenous companies by 21%. Ethnic diversity also made companies 33% more likely to have industry-leading profitability. For Silicon Valley, the solution proposed by tech diversity leaders is to incorporate more viewpoints into the product. That begins by diversifying the field of product management."
